‘I will weave you a cloak of moonlight,’ Silra offered, ‘if you bring me the Moonflower’s nectar in return.’ Harkin, desperate, agreed. Silra wove the cloak from her own stolen moonlight—threads she had plucked from the sky over years of deceit—and gave it to him. But when Harkin returned with the nectar, Silra laughed. ‘The cloak was never yours to keep,’ she hissed, and with a flick of her wrist, she reclaimed the moonlight, leaving Harkin’s daughter in darkness.

The **Moon Spirit**, who had watched from the heavens, grew furious. That night, as Silra slept, the spirit sent a **silver moth** to her loom. The moth’s wings were made of the same moonlight Silra had stolen, and as it fluttered, it began to **unweave her tapestries**, thread by thread. Silra woke to find her life’s work—her stolen dreams, her deceitful bargains—all unraveling before her.

The punishment was cruel: for every thread the moth unraveled, Silra’s own body began to **fray like old cloth**. Her fingers grew thin as spider legs, her skin translucent as silk. She tried to weave faster, to mend what she had broken, but the moth was relentless. The villagers, horrified, watched as Silra became a **living tapestry**, her body a patchwork of half-finished lies.

The cycle ended not with forgiveness, but with **emptiness**. When the last thread was unraveled, Silra dissolved into the wind, her essence scattered like dust. The Moon Spirit took back her stolen light, and the highlands of Veythar were never plagued by deceit again—though some say, on the darkest nights, you can still hear the whisper of a loom, weaving warnings into the wind."
